🤝 Handshake — Hackathon Project Brief
A deal isn't a deal until someone puts their hand out.

What You're Building
Handshake is a micro-contract app. Two people negotiate the terms of anything — a bet, a split, a dare, a pact — in a real-time shared thread. They propose, edit, argue. When both parties are satisfied, they simultaneously hold a button for 3 seconds.

It seals. Forever.

The contract lives at a permanent URL. Immutable. No takebacks. No edits. Just two names, a timestamp, and the terms you agreed to. No legal weight — pure social weight.

Core User Flow
Create contract → Share link → Negotiate in real-time → Both hold to seal → Permanent URL
User A creates a contract and writes the first draft of terms
User A shares the link with User B
Both parties can propose edits — each edit is a new entry in the negotiation log
When both are happy, they each hold the Seal button for 3 seconds simultaneously
The contract freezes. A permanent, shareable, read-only page is generated.
The Interesting Engineering Problems
These are the bits worth thinking about — not "how do I render a button", but the actual meaty decisions:

The simultaneous hold mechanic — both users must hold for 3 seconds at the same time. How do you sync that state? What's the UX if one person lets go? What's the timeout window?
True immutability — once sealed, no Convex mutation should ever touch that document again. Enforce this at the data layer, not just the UI.
The negotiation log — each proposed edit should be attributed and timestamped. Think append-only. Think audit trail.
Access control — only the two named signatories can edit. Anyone with the link can view. How do you model that cleanly with Clerk identities?
Technical Stack
Layer	Tool
Frontend	React + Vite
UI Components	shadcn/ui
Database / Backend	Convex
Auth	Clerk
Hosting	Vercel (deploy from GitHub)
Language	TypeScript throughout
Why this stack makes sense for this app
Convex handles the real-time negotiation sync without you writing a single WebSocket. Reactive queries mean both parties see edits instantly. Convex mutations give you transactional guarantees for the seal event.
Clerk gives each contract two verified identities — no anonymous seals.
Vercel + GitHub means you can ship from your terminal with git push. No ops, no config.
Suggested Convex Schema
// contracts
{
  id: Id<"contracts">,
  status: "negotiating" | "sealed",
  creatorId: string,          // Clerk user ID
  counterpartyId: string | null,
  terms: string,              // current working draft
  sealedAt: number | null,
  sealedTerms: string | null, // frozen copy at seal time
}

// negotiation_log
{
  contractId: Id<"contracts">,
  authorId: string,
  proposedTerms: string,
  createdAt: number,
}

// seal_intent
{
  contractId: Id<"contracts">,
  userId: string,
  holdStartedAt: number,
}
